<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-existence-uniqueness" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Consequences of Existence and Uniqueness</title>

  <p>
    The phase diagram method we developed on the previous page is powerful, but you
    might be wondering why it actually works. Why does the sign of <m>f(y)</m> tell
    us the long-term behavior of solutions? Why can't a solution just jump from one
    region to another? The answer comes from a fundamental theorem about autonomous
    differential equations. We aren't going to dwell on the theorem itself, but we need to understand how
    its consequences give us a much cleaner picture of the behavior of solutions and why
    our stability analysis is reliable.
  </p>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-existence-uniqueness-autonomous">
    <title>Existence and Uniqueness for First-Order Autonomous DEs</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose we are solving the first-order autonomous DE
        <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt} = f(y)</m>, where <m>f</m> and <m>f'(y)</m> are continuous.
        Then given any initial value <m>y(0) = y_0</m>:
        <ul>
          <li><p>A solution exists.</p></li>
          <li><p>The solution is unique.</p></li>
          <li><p>Solutions do not intersect.</p></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>

  <solution>
    <title>Optional: full technical statement</title>
    <p>
      The theorem above is somewhat simplified. The full statement is:
      suppose <m>f(y)</m> and <m>\dfrac{\partial f}{\partial y}</m> are continuous
      on some open region <m>R</m> of the <m>ty</m>-plane containing the point
      <m>(t_0, y_0)</m>. Then there exists an interval <m>(t_0 - h, t_0 + h)</m>
      for some <m>h \gt 0</m> on which a unique solution to
      <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt} = f(y)</m> with <m>y(t_0) = y_0</m> exists.
      Since our equation is autonomous (no <m>t</m> on the right-hand side),
      we can take <m>t_0 = 0</m> without loss of generality.
    </p>
  </solution>

  <p>
    The video below walks through the reasoning behind each of the consequences
    listed here. We will not write out all the reasoning in the notes — what matters
    most is understanding and applying the results, which we do on this page immediately after the video.
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="video-existence-uniqueness">
    <caption>This video explains how the theorem implies the consequences below, which is not contained in the notes.</caption>
    <video xml:id="yt-existence-uniqueness" youtube="0wMH13u7JzI" width="90%"/>
  </figure>

  <observation xml:id="obs-eu-consequences">
    <title>Consequences of Existence and Uniqueness</title>
    <p>
      In a first-order autonomous ODE <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt} = f(y)</m>, the following apply to continuous solutions <m>y(t)</m>:
      <ol>
        <li><p>
          <alert>A solution that starts at an equilibrium value stays there.</alert>
          If <m>y(t) = M</m> is an equilibrium solution, then the only solution
          with <m>y(0) = M</m> is <m>y(t) = M</m> itself. No other solution can
          pass through a point on an equilibrium.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <alert>Solutions grow or decrease forever.</alert>
          Since the sign of <m>f(y)</m> is constant within each zone between equilibria,
          and solutions cannot intersect one another, a solution that starts out
          increasing stays increasing for its entire interval of existence,
          and similarly for decreasing solutions.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <alert>Solutions are trapped between equilibria.</alert>
          Because solutions are continuous and cannot cross an equilibrium
          (by consequence 1), a solution that starts between two
          adjacent equilibria stays between them for its entire interval of existence.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <alert>Convergence to stable equilibria.</alert>
          A solution that is increasing and trapped below an equilibrium <m>M</m>
          (with no other equilibrium between them) must converge to <m>M</m>
          as <m>t \to \infty</m>. Similarly, a decreasing solution trapped above
          an equilibrium must converge to it.
        </p></li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </observation>

  <p>
    These consequences show that the phase diagram is useful for determining the long-term behavior of solutions.
    For example, in consequence 2, we see that determining whether a continuous solution is growing or decreasing forever
    is determined purely by which region <m>P(0)</m> falls in. For <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = 2P(P-10)</m>:
    if <m>P(0) \in (-\infty, 0)</m> or <m>P(0) \in (10, \infty)</m>, then <m>P(t)</m>
    grows forever. If <m>P(0) \in (0, 10)</m>, then <m>P(t)</m> decreases forever.
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="fig-phase-grows">
    <caption>
      Long-term behavior of solutions to <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = 2P(P-10)</m>
      based on initial value.
    </caption>
    <interactive xml:id="interactive-phase-grows"
      iframe="ch2-graph/phase-diagram-grows.html" width="100%" aspect="4:1.3">
      <static>
        <p>
          Phase diagram for <m>dP/dt = 2P(P-10)</m> showing which initial values
          lead to solutions that grow forever versus decrease forever.
        </p>
      </static>
    </interactive>
  </figure>

  <p>
    We can also read stability directly from the phase diagram, which relates to consequence 4. If arrows on both
    sides of an equilibrium point toward it, the equilibrium is stable, meaning nearby
    solutions converge to it. If arrows on both sides point away, it is unstable.
    For this example, <m>P = 0</m> is stable and <m>P = 10</m> is unstable.
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="fig-phase-stability">
    <caption>
      Stability of equilibrium solutions to <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = 2P(P-10)</m>
      read from the phase diagram.
    </caption>
    <interactive xml:id="interactive-phase-stability"
      iframe="ch2-graph/phase-diagram-stability.html" width="100%" aspect="4:1.3">
      <static>
        <p>
          Phase diagram for <m>dP/dt = 2P(P-10)</m> with stability labels.
          <m>P = 0</m> is stable since arrows point toward it from both sides.
          <m>P = 10</m> is unstable since arrows point away on both sides.
        </p>
      </static>
    </interactive>
  </figure>

  <remark xml:id="rem-doomsday-continuity">
    <title>A Note on "Growing Forever" and the Doomsday Case</title>
    <p>
      When we say a solution "grows forever," the doomsday example from
      <xref ref="sec-pop-doomsday"/> deserves a careful look. In that example,
      the solution with <m>P(0) \gt M</m> starts above the upper equilibrium
      and is increasing. The solution remains continuous
      and stays above <m>M</m> on its entire interval of existence <m>[0, T)</m>,
      and it blows up to infinity as <m>t \to T^-</m>. So it does grow forever,
      but only up to time <m>T</m>, and the model breaks down at doomsday.
    </p>
    <p>
      For <m>t \gt T</m>, if we allow discontinuous solutions, the formula continues
      to give values, but the solution jumps from <m>+\infty</m> to large negative
      values at <m>T</m>, which is physically meaningless for a population and not
      a continuous solution. In particular, it is not accurate
      to say <m>P(t) \to \infty</m> as <m>t \to \infty</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      In the stability analysis that follows, we will classify solutions starting
      above an upper non-stable equilibrium as "growing forever" without distinguishing
      the finite-time blowup case from true growth to infinity. The phase diagram
      correctly captures the direction of this behavior either way.
    </p>
  </remark>

  <p>
    Before we move onto more complicated examples, let's make sure we understand how deduce some behavior
     from a phase diagram. Consider the phase diagram below for a population model <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = f(P)</m>.
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="fig-phase-mc">
    <caption>
      Phase diagram for a population model with equilibria at <m>P = 0</m> and <m>P = 10</m>.
    </caption>
    <interactive xml:id="interactive-phase-mc"
      iframe="ch2-graph/phase-diagram-mc.html" width="100%" aspect="5:1">
      <static>
        <p>
          Phase diagram for a population model with equilibrium solutions at <m>P = 0</m>
          and <m>P = 10</m>, marked as dots on a number line. An arrow points left for
          <m>P \lt 0</m> (solutions decreasing), right for <m>0 \lt P \lt 10</m>
          (solutions increasing), and left for <m>P \gt 10</m> (solutions decreasing).
        </p>
      </static>
    </interactive>
  </figure>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-mc-grows-forever">
    <statement>
      <p>
        In the phase diagram above: for which values of <m>P(0)</m> does the solution <m>P(t)</m> grow forever?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="no">
      <choice>
        <statement><p><m>P(0) \in (-\infty, 0) \cup (10, \infty)</m></p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Not quite. Check the arrow directions in those regions — do they point
            right (increasing) or left (decreasing)?
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p><m>P(0) \in (0, 10)</m></p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Correct! In the region <m>0 \lt P \lt 10</m>, the arrow points right,
            so solutions are increasing and grow forever. By consequence 4, since
            the solution is trapped below <m>P = 10</m> and increasing, it
            converges to <m>P = 10</m>. So it grows forever, just not without bound.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement><p><m>P(0) \in (0, \infty)</m></p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Not quite. Look at what happens for <m>P(0) \gt 10</m> — the arrow
            points left, meaning solutions are decreasing there.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement><p>No solution grows forever.</p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Not quite. Look at the arrow in the middle region — it points right,
            meaning solutions there are increasing for their entire interval of existence.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
  </exercise>

  <p>
    Notice that in this case, <m>P(t)</m> grows forever but not without bound. It
    converges to the stable equilibrium <m>P = 10</m> while it increases for all <m>t>0</m>. This is different from the
    doomsday case, where solutions grow forever <em>and</em> blow up to infinity
    in finite time.
  </p>

<interactive xml:id="question-form-2-2-4" iframe="question-form.html?section=2.2.4" width="100%" aspect="2:1"/>
</section>
